The diet of an obese child: no breakfast and a steaming dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight, while 9 percent of school-age children are overweight and 5 percent are obese.
And obese children are more likely to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as a recent survey has shown.
Once again, the environment in which we grow and the patterns around us are important to the healthy development of the human being.
For example, tablecloths in obese children are up to half as likely to be clogged as those in families of normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of obese people ate French fries for dinner the day before a study linked to a global campaign called Obesity is Not a coincidence.
The families of the obese also tended to be less athletic, but this is true of most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of the children said their parents found time for physical activity at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the Obesity is No Accident event, sponsored by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 pupils from grades 4 to 8 have participated in the project.
Proper diet and adequate exercise in the family are among the factors that have led to a dramatic increase in the number of overweight and even obese children.
"For example, only half of those questioned said they ate breakfast-eat-lunch-eat-eat-dinner five times a day, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition", says one survey.
No breakfast and no dinner
Experts point out that even relative details, such as a regular family breakfast, are essential to healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of schoolchildren's families eat breakfast at the same time.
Most families eat breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding out that ten percent of the households don't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper diet.
The questionnaire showed that obese children's families are much more likely to consume unhealthy fries.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks a sugary soda every day (70 percent).
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly participate in sports, less than half of the parents - 15 percent - did.
Make your own menu
The second part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own menu according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition".
Their favorite foods include many meats, sweets, and meats.
"The high prevalence of sweet lemonade is particularly alarming", says the final report of the survey.
For lunch, pasta won the day over poultry.
But the children practically didn't want legumes, and the popularity of fish and vegetable lunch is low.
Health Care
The study also showed that children are willing to change their eating habits if given the right information.
"A control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire at the end of the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' seminar showed a significant shift in preference towards healthy eating principles in a number of cases", the project results state.
It was particularly striking in the sweet soda scene, where more children would have preferred plain water.
Children were also much more likely to cross off poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and to limit sweet foods and dumplings.
