In Need for Speed: The Run, you race across America.
Other
What started out as a carefree drive turns into a routine morning shift due to a series of completely unnecessary lazy mistakes.
While the ambition was largely achieved, it was not worth it if no one was willing to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, was highly anticipated upon its release.
He promised to take the long-running Need for Speed series in a new direction, and from the game's graphics, it seemed like a game that could not be outdone in the action racing genre.
We were also curious to see what would happen to the inserted passages in which the main character gets out of the car and runs around.
But as is the custom with the NFS series, a lot of it turns out a little different than we expected.
They're potentially decent arcade races, but the whole thing just brings down a few unnecessary bugs that have been running in the series for years or so.
So, these aren't actually mistakes, but rather some kind of inexplicable laxity on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story in which the protagonist Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution he offers to participate in an illegal race across America.
You're driving down the west coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to be the first to New York.
There are some interesting elements to the idea.
The circuit is divided into ten stages, followed by more than fifty races.
This means that each race is run on a different track and that the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It's not like the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of graphics is similar to the previous parts of the series.
So it's not a world war.
But driving across the desert, through the autumn landscape, or high up in the snow-capped mountains is visually very pleasant.
And the races are occasionally colored with some unusual elements.
In the desert, for example, you may be caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you must be careful not to be caught in an avalanche.
Besides, the races are pretty well set up.
There's only a few types, but that's enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the required number of competitors (basically a classic race), then you try to catch up (a classic match with a stopwatch), and then you have a duel with a single opponent.
And the police are involved from time to time, making your efforts even more unpleasant.
New is the passages outside the vehicle.
It's more like an interactive animation where Jack is mostly running away from someone and you have to help him by pushing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not that complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer of these passages in the play than you might expect (maybe even only three).
But in the end, it's to the good of the thing, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above, it's one of the elements that make the game more layered.
The ride pattern follows the pattern of the previous parts.
That means it's definitely not a big deal these days, but it's not a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But in the realm of racing, the local driving pattern is still quite good, although we could do better than the competition.
So far, everything is perfectly fine.
But the problems start to show up after a while.
Unlike the road model, the collision model is not in good shape.
We don't expect a game of this type to calculate complex deformation and collision, but if you have no idea of how your car will behave before you hit anything, then it's probably not all that bad.
Typically, in close overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lick each other lightly, but other times in almost identical situations, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even attack.
With the restart system, it doesn't really bother you, but it sure does.
Restarts are designed so that if you get beaten or run far off the track, the game throws you back to the last point of interception on the track.
But only five restarts are available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a "if things go wrong" kind of thing, rather than a "you can count on that" kind of thing.
But sometimes even the re-parties don't help, they're solved by the need to learn a particular section of the race by heart.
The great downside of games is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners require you to make a specific way to go, or you simply cannot get into them.
Other times, you'll find civilian vehicles in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
It's especially irritating in situations where you see the other car in front of you passing between two opposing cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get to them, because it's "calculated" so that the situation always happens right under your nose.
The rivals have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you'll come across several places where, again, regardless of the time, you'll always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
It's most striking at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you're going in the opposite direction.
The enemy must get there before you, obviously, at any cost.
Because when it's in front of you, it makes it harder to see the cars in front of you, so you're probably going to get a little bit messy at first.
The intention to make the game more thrilling and adrenaline-fuelled is understandable, but the execution is so obvious that you'll get bored easily.
And that's a shame, because even though it's a simple ride, it's fun to play and sometimes so action-packed that you literally don't have time to see where it's flying.
And it doesn't matter if it's the 50 unique tracks, the race sequencing that doesn't allow for boredom, or whatever.
The unconventional idea is to change cars during races.
You have to be careful at the roadside gas stations because that's where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you'll settle for what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, heavy American bikes for smooth highways, and exotic super sports for technical driving, such as on winding mountain roads.
And with the main story mode, there's also a challenge mode, which is racing in the locations that you know from the story.
Here, you not only earn medals, but experience points for your profile, which is common to both the challenge and the story.
To get a higher level of driver, various items are unlocked: from cars to wallpapers for the profile.
It is also back-linked to the online Autolog function, which compares your scores with other players and provides additional community features, among other things.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
You drive your car into a subway tunnel, where you ride the tracks in the dark.
The speedometer flashes between 90 and 120 miles an hour, and the subway train is coming up behind you, and you're being uncompromisingly scrapped.
We'll probably have a debate in the newsroom for a few days about whether or not anyone really thought a bit about the game when they made it, or whether or not the writers think we're really that big of a jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It freezes so that at certain moments of tension, the imaging drops, in some cases quite tragically.
But it's mostly for larger groups of people, where you're not going to get any of the smooth-scan stuff.
The soundtrack is fine, and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a wider, younger audience, the soundtrack was created in the category of "every dog is different", but it can be assumed that because of the music, people will not buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so very embarrassing.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would be safe to say that The Run is the best NFS game in years.
But this is how the game works.
I'm sure it's fun, but be prepared to have your mistakes bludgeoned into the air with the power of airport headlights.
