To the general public, IBM is a symbol of technological revolution, a company perceived as very modern, yet it was founded a hundred years ago.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by the company's first chief, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already made it clear that many of the world's problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" became the imprint around which the life of the future giant would revolve (as well as the name of an internal IBM magazine that began publication in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully constructed corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continually moving toward the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a century because it stayed true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else.
That's what's allowed us to transform technology, business and society in our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the next century", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the firm's current director.
A sophisticated system
In the 1930s, Watson's approach to caring for his employees was similar to that of the Czech entrepreneur Baťa - the people at IBM were among the first American employees to have paid vacation, employer's insurance plus a sleek employee uniform and a sophisticated system to reward the best inventors and traders.
Well, as elaborate as it is, IBM has a long-term relationship with a customer.
The company was a genius at harnessing talent from the very beginning -- one of the first companies in the world to eliminate any discrimination so that they could choose.
In line with the company's anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisano to be replaced as IBM's CEO by a woman, Virginia Rometty, next year.
She's been with IBM for 30 years, still holding the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
IBM has been doing what's called jams, online brainstorming, in recent years, and a lot of future strategies and innovations have come out of it.
No wonder the company has so many ideas - it employs almost half a million people.
Institutions with a good reputation
The firm's strong internal and external image ensures its position in the business.
"From the beginning, IBM was more of an institution than a technology company", said Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM, to The Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems by using technology", added George Colony of the consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there's a difference between entering the market and actually creating the market.
IBM, or "Big Blue", as it is known in the United States because of its logo, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a hundred years.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company - developing hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won Nobel Prizes.
Her inventions include the ATM, the credit card, the financial swap, the bar code, and the disk.
IBM, with about $220 billion, became the second-largest technology company this year by market capitalization (first is Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of the customers and the times - IBM, for example, did not bet on its own operating system OS/2, on-line services Prodigy or IBM PCjr.
"If your business is built on moving forward, you cannot emotionally cling to the past", notes Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms - and if they don't work, they leave.
Unlike, say, the rival Microsoft, which basically stands on Windows.
Prospective technologies
IBM's biggest sales share is in services, with software and hardware accounting for about one-fifth.
In 1990, hardware was still the strongest player with more than half of the market share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold off $15 billion worth of low-yield assets, while investing $58 billion to buy promising technologies.
It has continued to invest since 2008, when the world first experienced the modern financial crisis.
IBM is following the example of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to be coming through the current crisis unscathed.
The IBM stock price has risen by a rocketing 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, and the company's net profit has been rising steadily.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but its values.
So it's safe to assume that if the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will be able to handle it.
IBM history: from cheese-cutter to space travel
IBM, the International Business Machines, was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally under the complicated name of the Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 - originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for what would later become IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history stretches back to the 1880s.
They had technologies such as the famous "pigeons", or clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then represented the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still the foundation of an unconquerable corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started out by making and selling all kinds of machines for businesses - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson headed the company, it doubled in sales to nine million dollars and began a massive expansion of the company to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly 40 years in the top job, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., succeeded him.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960's, IBM's computers and humans helped NASA to control space missions to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous manned flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "kit" that set the computer standard at the time, called the IBM 5150 was released in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer business to the Chinese company Lenovo, and in turn bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to focus on consulting and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has been following for the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to use technology intelligently, in areas that may not have been planned yet, and to improve things, for example, in transport and urban management.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which helps merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the domestic market as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM ČR, the company also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Centre is based in Prague and has a world-class voice recognition research team.
