How fares have changed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in the then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold overwhelmingly only trips to the socialist bloc countries, since travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled to the East (GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime sided with the West and the visits of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed a letter of invitation from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but you had to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" at the travel agency.
But it still wasn't won.
The so-called foreign exchange allowance, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange guarantee it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for travel to the West.
By far the most common holiday was spent in the Czech lands, resulting in a large number of huts and cottages that the Czechs acquired, and this custom survives to this day.
Thus, since 1989, Czech travel has undergone a real revolution.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our max, last year 4.5 million Czechs spent holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
The huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that Croatia, the most popular country for us today, was not a free country to travel to until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia.
The abolition of visa requirements for Western European neighbours in the late 1990s triggered a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Austria's Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovakians could not get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tents in the parks because our incomes at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was to carry their own food, canned food, sausages, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the free Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to finally buy Western currency after many years of being unable to do so.
But our standard of living, and with it, average wages, were rising, which led to another important moment around 1997.
With increased travel demand, travel agencies began to arrange tours by charter flights on a regular basis from 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past, thanks to the possibility of contracting quantity discounts.
By the late 1990's, the Czechs had visa-free access to virtually every developed country in the world except the United States, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to exotics, from the Czech Republic, was sent to Thailand due to a significant demand.
Starting this year, direct charters to warm distant countries are taking off with Czech tourists every year, and this winter, there will be direct flights from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The exotic country is now visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists, and our country was finally ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history, and spent more than CZK 15 000 per person for a single holiday abroad including costs at the place of stay for the first time in history.
