A Massacre on a Personal Level
Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a list of characters that makes you dizzy.
A word of advice for the moment: carefully tear out this page and make it a backup.
You will get to know all the characters in Mr. Englund's novel very well, and this list will serve as a navigation - a beacon - at times when, like the men and women in the story, you feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He's also the new vice-president of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we're talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "an anti-historical work".
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties, and famous battles, but it is almost devoid of ambassadors, energetic journalists, and discussions of tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains the author, as "a book about what it was like".
"Beauty and the Sorrow" combines the wartime experiences of 20 more-or-less dozen men and women on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and civil servants.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go insane, or die.
Their lives are like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones added to the web of destiny while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classical historical novels.
It dispels the notion that World War I was all about the horrifying trench fighting on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where the war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
In this book, the soldiers deal with the problems of being hit by a beehive, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or dealing with the presence of tsetse flies.
It's a very moving read almost from the beginning.
War will consume people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina with the stench of gunpowder.
When the cannon fire starts in the distance and you're a woman at home with your children, will you run or stay?
Who's coming, anyhow?
Almost no one understands what is happening, or even why the whole war has been started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts", Mr. Englund observed, "was filled with conjecture, conjecture, hope, fear, prejudice, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and the Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are all taken from biographies, letters and other published material.
Their life stories may sound terrifying and fascinating, but the inclusion of minute moments and details make them vivid and believable.
Many of them are about suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Substitutions, substitutions everywhere".
"Coffee embossed, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, and wooden buttons". That's what I was thinking.
He goes on to describe food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "rice pressed in sheep fat (with a fake wooden bone), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peels, wooden-soled shoes".
