Walls have eyes: How scientists are studying you on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who was presenting his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July killing spree that left 77 people dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
While Breivik could have acted alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time on the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting the right-wing group on social media pages.
After this summer's tragedy, scientists are eager to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - just go to the Facebook.
"We realised that it's not that hard to get them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a UK research team on digital populism in Europe.
The pool of personal information on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that it was enough for researchers to simply use ads on the site to pinpoint the target demographic with absolute accuracy - something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, and they targeted them and sent them ads, but instead of inviting them to the new group or offering them dietary products, they asked them to fill out questionnaires that asked questions about their level of education, their attitude to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men, driven by rising immigration rates.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen".
The DEMOS team's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and policy researchers use these sites to study everything from health issues to social trends to hidden status updates, wall posts and clicked "like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users, each of whom provides an average of three pieces of data a day, making it a "information supernova" that is driving a lot of new research.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to bother them on the street.
"It used to be that if you wanted to do a poll of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You'd have to get into a party that would never let you in", says Bartlett.
"Facebook is taking all of this down - you just go straight to them".
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify social health problems and avoid them.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that college students who discussed their drinking habits on Facebook were much more likely to have a drinking problem than college students who were silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
"You can't solve a problem if you can't diagnose it", Dimitri Christakis, co-author of the study with Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify at-risk children that we wouldn't have had a chance to find otherwise".
Facebook itself is constantly probing its users' data.
The site's information team compiled statistics on the relationship of relationship status to Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010 and the nation's satisfaction rate (mainly using information they had access to - advocates of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information available for research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is tracking them whether they like it or not - in exchange for the chance to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site must give their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules for how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
"I think most users didn't even think that scientists could look at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he did using his students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it as a matter of information between themselves and their friends".
Next, the question of methodology is also to be considered.
Even when research is done offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There's no way to verify how much of the information on a profile and posts on a wall is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, feels that pencil and notebook remain the best possible tools to use in research.
"Going out into the real world and talking to real people is something that cannot be replaced", he says.
