Four times during the interview, there's a long pause between the question and the answer -- 10 to 15 seconds of thought, where you see Jobs perfectly think through the answer to be as precise and as accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient with Cringely's questions, and urges him to get to the more important problems and issues faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, and it's filled with eerily prophetic thoughts as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong, offering his own vision of the future in the computer technology field.
It's one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here as an avid dreamer in the prime of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
It was not long before, after he had expressed his thoughts, he began to put them into practice as well.
