How to Tell When a Lie Is True
A glance at recent headlines reveals the seriousness and pervasiveness of lies and deception in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy with accusations that he sexually harassed several women - both sides claim the other is lying.
Administrators at Penn State University were accused of perjury when they tried to suppress a record of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on camera telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and destabilized many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing campaign funds to try to conceal his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that erupted around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
There are stories of cheating at school and university all over the place.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their own assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending a message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How many scams are we dealing with?
Studies show that you lie anywhere from 10 to 200 times a day.
Let's assume that many of them are charitable lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first encounter in life.
Detecting lies, or "detecting lies", is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it's not a social game, like, say, a charade, where a person shouts, "I've got you". Deception detection is a serious branch of science, working with scientific data gathered over the last six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're snuggling, or making cocktails, or blushing, or getting tattoos.
But don't assume that liars are difficult to spot and detect.
A trained lie detector can detect the truth from sentence structure, subtle facial expressions, the way questions are formulated, and their timing.
I've spent years gathering scientific evidence from the vast and growing field of lie detection, and it's clear that deception detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and can help you a lot in today's complex world -- especially if your job involves hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing people.
Good liars can read other people, let them cool off in their vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively perceive how the other party is perceiving them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "other-centered" lies -- often to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less to their partners than single people (but the lies they tell are often "horrible").
We also know that if you're perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know when someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
It's called "initial observation".
It'll give him something to compare it to later.
Notice the subject's posture, his laugh, his voice work.
You should know if someone is habitually tapping their feet so that you don't falsely accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But consider these only warning signs, not proof of a lie.
People who tell a lie may stop moving their upper body as they try to remember their invented story, turn the tips of their shoes toward the door, lean out, change their posture significantly, or exhibit "after-conversation relief" - exaggerated relief breathing and a change of position when difficulty is behind them.
People who do interviews often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see how much relief there is after the interview is over.
Also feel the subject's language.
There's a famous story about how Scott Peterson once crossed over and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which led to a nationwide search for her body.
Lying individuals may also express themselves in a measured way: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question over and over.
The most common verbal signs are very minor.
One can use a lot of "softening language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge".
Such a response leaves much to be desired, and it is often another warning sign.
There is no spell that can expose every lie, but it is possible to develop skills that can detect a lie.
Such skills will help you to avoid being a liar and a cheater in your personal and professional life.
