Climate change has crippled the economy
During the first year of the government of María López Valdez, unemployment and insecurity increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined, and with it the economy
The year 2011 will be recorded in Sinaloa's economic history as the first year of the government of María López Valdez, who calls herself the government of change, and brought with it high expectations for economic progress, but due to the adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth was recorded and even the main indicators of economic development declined.
The low temperatures in February caused losses of millions in agriculture, limited the growth potential of the national economy, and were responsible for a decline in economic activity of 3.6% in the first half of this year.
According to a damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares of cultivated land were damaged, with 78.03% completely destroyed and 21.07% partially damaged.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state increased during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population.
Less liquidity
According to Gerardo López Cervantese, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps that have been taken at the level of public policy.
"We are seeing rising unemployment related to a variety of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the limited resources due to the legislation passed by Congress in the fight against money laundering, and it is not easy for people who illegally take dollars to earn, invest or use them", he said.
Stopping the migration
López Cervantes said that demographic factors also contributed to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of the difficulty of entering and because even when they do, it is difficult for them to get jobs, so people stay and demand jobs from our state, and unemployment is rising", he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is also worsened by the increasing unreliability that prevails in the area of working conditions.According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state work without paying benefits to the social security administration.
In addition to unemployment and unreliability, other characteristics of the labor market include low wages, which are the lowest in the country according to the registers of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 pesetas by September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, 2011 also saw the biggest drop in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years.According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697 in the January-June period, a decrease of 87,74% compared to $5,143,312 in the same period the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government reports investments of PTE 17 280 million per year, mainly in service companies.
Debt and other liabilities
In a scenario of economic decline, the state government asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be allocated to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to revive the economy.
Reaction
According to business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés showed a lack of government management skills.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformative Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of coordination of will between the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The economic development in Sinaloa has been really modest this year, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, we have to double our efforts in 2012, there was a lack of harmonization of all our efforts and especially the proper and synchronized functioning of this new government, and we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Loredo López said events like the frost earlier this year had halted the state's economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic momentum was caused by a number of events, including frost, and one of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to regain the momentum needed to achieve acceptable levels of movement of processes, products and services.
Redefining the Mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Republic of Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"We generally see that work is being done, we believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and the economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The Work Ahead of Us
The Coparmex Chairman stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better guide the Government's efforts.
"Generally, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in different areas, some progress has been made in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan", he said.
He said the current administration has shown progress in public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that there is work being done and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us", he said.
