"The same thing happened to us in the previous six-year period because the state did not have the economic capacity to participate and the programmes went ahead.
Despite the fact that there is a promise from the state representatives regarding the transfer of these resources, he said that a request was sent to Armando Villarreal, the secretary for administration and finance, to speed up the process and the corresponding percentage to arrive as soon as possible.
"We were supposed to get 12 million, and even though the year is coming to an end, we still haven't gotten a peso".
Court approves "end of analog broadcasting" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Republic (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional action brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that aims to accelerate the so-called "deactivation of analogue signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juana Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his authority when he issued a decree outlining the steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
The action brought by the Senate was dismissed as a result, since the qualified majority of eight votes required to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree in question was not obtained, and the decree remains in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olgou Sánchez Cordero, proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all issues related to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel).
The only people who voted for the project were Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight the decree.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive could not structure through general standards measures to prepare the public administration.
"I don't think even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", he said, noting that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, related to better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
It believes that delaying change would delay the benefits of digitisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, as digitisation is not only technical but also 'concerns economic, social, political and national security issues'.
As he stressed, these issues "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition and had done so through their governments, even though they had highly specialised technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it was not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent interfered with the area of congressional jurisdiction, to introduce into the area of administration the observance of laws prepared by the legislative power.
In Michoacán, they're analyzing the possibility of a voice-by-voice count.
According to the PREP data, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is less than 27 percent, and 879 of the 6,074 precincts have not yet been counted.
The "vote by vote" option emerged in this year's election in Michoacán, where according to the data published by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is less than 27 percent, and 879 votes out of a total of 6074 constituencies have not yet been counted.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of measures to harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not officially ratify its political constitution, nor its State Electoral Code or the Law on Electoral Justice, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this election period, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication within the deadline set by the Law of the Official State Gazette, saying that he had some objections against them.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative power and declared the vote of the head of state on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" because it has no right to "approve or veto".
Asked about the possibility of counting "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the General Council of the IEM, it would be possible for the partial and total counting to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, a partial counting of one or more ballots will be possible under the following conditions: the election results do not match; there is no record of the vote count and the calculation in the relevant box or the President does not have it available; or there are errors and obvious irregularities in the election results.
In addition, a total recount of votes in all polling stations will be possible if there is evidence that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request is made at the beginning of the session by a representative of the party and/or coalition that has proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recount may also be carried out if, after a proper count, the difference between the likely winner and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, and whenever there is an explicit request from the second-placed political party, in which case the ballots for which a partial recount has been carried out shall be discarded.
It should be noted that this is the situation in the elections in Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second places is less than 0.16%, even though 129 of the total 923 constituencies have not yet been counted.
His last will and testament.
His ashes will be scattered in the Zapaliname mountains, the family confirmed.
The remains of pilot Felipe Bacio Cortes were transported to Saltillo, his hometown, on Sunday night, with a solemn ceremony and funeral mass on Monday.
According to the family, the lieutenant colonel's last wish was that his ashes be scattered in the Zapalinama Mountains.
After receiving the highest honors along with the other people who died in the accident, the Bacio Cortés family returned to the capital of Coahuila on a Mexican Air Force plane, where they and their closest friends attended the ceremony in Campo Marte.
At noon, the ashes of the lieutenant colonel arrived at the chapel located in the street Nazario Ortiz Garza, where also came family and friends.
At 5:30 p.m., a farewell ceremony was held at the Saltillo Institute of Technology, organized by his former high school technologists and members of the football team, of which Felipe Bacio was a member during his graduation.
"He wanted to return to Saltilla and his wish was that his ashes be scattered in the Zapalinama mountains, as he always told his family and friends", said Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister.
She said the lieutenant colonel had fulfilled all his wishes, was at the top of his game, "he was a wonderful man, an extraordinary father, son, a loving brother who lived for his family".
Felipe Bacio Cortés left the town of Saltillo at a very young age and entered the Colegio del Aire flying school in Zapopán, Jalisco.
Some people didn't believe it because they said he even drove a truck, but he always followed his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio remembers him as a very good man, "he had just arrived in Saltillo, the whole family wanted to see him, as when he brought Martha Sahagún to Saltillo".
The young man even recalls that when he was seven years old, he went to Zapopan to attend his uncle's graduation, so he is convinced that he died doing what he loved most in life: flying a plane.
They said their last good-byes
With Felipe Bacio Cortés, Lieutenant Colonel of the Mexican Air Force, we said goodbye to all the honors that came to him from Governor Jorge Torres López, the citizens and the government of the state, the Mexican Army through the Sixth Military Zone, the Mexican Air Force itself, senior officials and students of the Technological High School of Saltillo, where he studied in 1985 and where he excelled both in studies and sports.
Bacio Cortés died days ago after the helicopter he was piloting crashed, with the Secretary of State, José Francisco Blake Mora, and six other people on board, all officials of this state.
At 18:05, the remains of Bacio Cortés, a native of Saltillo, arrived (crucified) to be handed over to the Mexican Air Force, under the leadership of Major Jaime Martinez, in the square, where in the meantime the family, his daughter Amanda and wife Cristina, mother, siblings and other relatives, students and teachers gathered.
Three abandoned dead bodies were found at the estate of Cadereyta NL
Several hours before the discovery, military officials introduced to the media 11 individuals who had been detained in the area for crimes related to organized crime.
The bodies of three men, shot in various parts of their bodies and heads, were found in an abandoned farmhouse in the municipality of Cadereyta Jiménez, Nuevo León.
The find was made on a mile of road from Cadereyta to Santiago, at the level of the area known as El Castillo.
People who moved around these places noticed that the beige-coffee-fence cottage had its door open from time to time.
When they looked in from a distance of about ten feet, they saw three bodies, so they alerted the authorities immediately.
One person was wearing a yellow sports shirt and dark cotton pants and was not wearing a boot, and next to him was another person in a white striped sports shirt.
A few yards away, the body of another person was found, wearing a red sports shirt and blue cotton pants.
All three of them were lying face down.
According to the information obtained at the scene, all three people were probably murdered in another place, because no bullets were found.
On the fence of the hut, messages were found addressed to one organized crime group by another, as well as a number of bullet marks, both on the building and on the door.
In Cadereyta, 11 suspects were arrested
The Secretary of National Defence has identified 11 individuals, including juveniles, who were members of a criminal group operating mainly in the Cadereyta area and linked to kidnappings, murders, persecutions and illegal burials.
According to the information published, in the first attempt on November 11th, in the colony of Los Alveros, 8 people were detained and one detainee was released.
Three properties and a cell phone were seized, and they confirmed they were members of a criminal group called "Los Zetas".
Another raid occurred at 6 a.m. on November 12th, when military personnel were on patrol in the Rancho Viejo area of Cadereyta when they spotted a car without a life jacket and two people inside.
