A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will confront the crisis that has kept this country above the brink of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to present him with a new government to face the crisis that has kept this country from the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone in danger.
The presidential palace issued a statement announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgi Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to form a government composed mostly of technocrats, though it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with the political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were being overcome.
"The frame is now well marked", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, a much shorter time than usual, while Italy struggled to combat the political and financial crisis that had driven its debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders, the only way to restore Italy's battered credibility.
Monti is under a lot of pressure to hurry, because of the volatility of the markets, the interest rates on Italy's 10-year BTP bonds have exceeded the 7% threshold, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of Italian employers' organization Confindustria, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this predicament.
Monti's hopes of success have been boosted by the support of the PDL's Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to be successful", Angelina Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now, a number of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government formed by Monti.
Support to Parliament
Monti's new government must have strong support in parliament to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacles or delays in this effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could spell disaster.
Monti began talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organisations.
The round ends Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who has made very rapid progress in responding to the crisis.
After a brief dip late last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields have returned to critical levels, reacting to uncertainty about the new prime minister's success.
Bailing out Italy, whose public debt is 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the capabilities of the euro area's current financial reserves.
Monti has said that his government should stay in power until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite the general forecasts that politicians will give him time only to implement reforms and then call early elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this government must be composed only of experts to get Italy out of the predicament the country is in because of financial pressure.
Political sources said that the mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicates the attempt to integrate both the government and the political establishment.
