The quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"The trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to deliver one of the greatest concerts of all time at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We've waited over 20 years, but the band themselves assure us that for them, the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is on the South American continent on their 20th anniversary tour and on Sunday the 20th, they will make a unique stop in Central America.
This day, he will perform from 7:30 p.m. at the National Stadium with the angel group The X and the national musicians of Las Robertas.
This is a sample of the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the website La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true, Pearl Jam will be playing in Costa Rica, do you realize what your fans are going through?
The trip to Costa Rica is also our dream come true.
We've been to South and Central America twice, and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, and it's a beautiful country, and I believe we can stay here for a few days.
So we're very excited to bring our music to you.
I ask because they love the band here, and the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your most ardent supporters?
Thank you for standing with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long.
Some people are already talking about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been created in a matter of weeks.
We've put on some great shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that'll get us into shape for the Costa Rica show.
We're actually looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle, and for both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and its surf-worthy waves?
We have a lot of fellow surfers, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends go to Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico to surf, and those are the best places to surf, and that's how we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love to surf.
Looking at your tour, you put on a great show with a lot of songs.
What are you planning for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, there's no limit to what we can do.
We're gonna try to put on a show that's as diverse as possible, and we're gonna try to play a couple of songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good, diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why would I do that?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everybody likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have a song or two in our repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on it and we're surprised because we remember why we liked it so much and maybe we've forgotten about it.
It makes the show more interesting for us, and I think it makes it more interesting for people.
This tour is celebrating 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe all that you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you do.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and stay in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much power we've been given and it's touching that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to see the places we've always wanted to see.
We couldn't have landed better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the birth of the grunge genre?
We've always been honored to be part of a group that's represented by all the greats.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising that when a movement starts from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
Occasionally, a group may form in a city, but it is much less common for five or ten groups to arise from one city at a time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them sometimes.
Last year we went to the festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're lucky to have all of them as friends, and we're honored to be a part of this movement that's been born in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is already much longer than the usual length of a band.
I think that, first of all, we're all lucky to be alive, and secondly, it's important that we're all constantly interested in each other.
We're all close friends, and because of that, we've been able to open up musical pathways that allow everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I think it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame has not been easy, but thanks to your success, you can do whatever you want.
