The 16 gates municipal tender reopens the debate on the role of the Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), which had already ceased to exist, the municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the CMB disappeared in 1987, the park returned to many people's minds as the upper limit of Barcelona, as the Catalan metropolis is one of the few that does not orient itself on the north-south axis, but up (up) - down (sea).
Qualifying Collserola as a nature reserve goes in that direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with the wild boars instead of the bear Yogi.
That was the position until September, when the City Council announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrances to Collserola.
The gate, of course, is more of a recording of the park's thoughts.
Either that, or someone's trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question is, Collserola, the park or the mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and from the reflection on the city, this question becomes the central theme of all the Barcelona architects.
It's as hot a subject as when two members of this old caste of elected officials meet in an elevator and shake hands.
And it was this feat that produced one of the rare coincidences between the thinking of three Barcelona architects and the leading university professors.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure is justified.
