The visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was conducted under visual flight rules, which means that the crew must be able to see the terrain during the flight.
The weather conditions:
The AICM report indicates adequate conditions at takeoff, according to which the aircraft is proceeding towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico, cloud layers were visible at low altitude.
Routes selected:
It is likely that due to the clouds, the crew searched for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the helicopter's last radar readings match, so it's likely that there was no loss of control or alteration of flight trajectory prior to impact.
Dispersion of aircraft debris within the restricted area:
The information we have at present allows us to assume that the impact was on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The scattered debris diagram indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of the impact.
No fire or explosion reported.
No evidence of an explosion or fire was recorded at the scene.
The latest test results indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
