Mexican Health Insurance Institute launches research on the gene that causes obesity
The Health Insurance Institute is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for child and adolescent obesity.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to identify the gene that causes obesity in children and adolescents.
In a report, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the National Center for 21st Century Specialist Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research is open to the general public, with or without a licence, and can be accessed at the participating IMSS sports centres in the Valle de México, where tests will be carried out on young people every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and that since October 8 this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (Eastern Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are collected, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity, and to trace the risk factors in Mexican children and young people, and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He said that every Saturday, all participants are anthropometrically measured (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (to try to identify genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health-care worker concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and a 47% increase in obesity in girls", said an IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of the Earth is different from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and five percent African genetic makeup, a fact reflected in the genes responsible for diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants was that they would receive an overall assessment of the children's condition, which would reveal whether they were overweight or obese.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential, and doctors give it to parents in writing, explaining all the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that involves a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using public transportation instead of walking short distances.
Obesity is also caused by a high caloric intake, i.e. a higher consumption of sugar-sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, breads, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content, and genetic load, which is the subject of this study.
There will be no gaps in the asphalt of UNAM.
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, is creating modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture with improved functionality, independent of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving were done properly, almost 200,000 potholes in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area would not need to be repaired after each rainy season, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, the potholes would be significantly reduced or even eliminated.
In his lecture "The Technological Cause of Dirt", given during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that a laboratory under his direction was developing modified asphalt with polymers, which would produce a mixture of asphalt and asphalt-like properties but with greater mechanical strength, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve functionality and reduce the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltene, and low molecular weight molecules called malten, which together give asphalt its typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to crack, he added.
This means that the strength of the asphalt on the streets is not uniform but varies during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, noted a chemical engineering expert.
A chemistry faculty scientist observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with a flexible tile made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is the asphalt layer, made up of small stones that are poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He pointed out that each stone that makes up the cartridge is covered with asphalt.
This allows the forces in the tile to be distributed well when cars pass or pressure is created.
If it were modified asphalt, they would have decomposed even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the asphalt cartridge is to be covered with a final layer, called a mantle, made of fine stone, that is, sand, also covered in asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle's rims, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and ensure road friction.
Since the coat will be subjected to a heavy load as part of the grooming, it must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken to ensure that the material is not too heavy.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to bear in mind.
Once the ground is wet, the water spreads inward and is hard to get out, causing all layers of the pavement to soften and form a pothole.
He explained that the first damage to the asphalt matrix occurs after the film has been destroyed during the formation of the voids, but that this damage does not occur in one moment, but is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs with appropriate maintenance programmes.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of debris, and therefore the thickness of each layer of paving must correspond to the load of the vehicles and must be guaranteed not to exceed this load.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that as far as asphalt is concerned, much work is still ahead and research is still in its early stages.
