Jordan's King Abdullah II was the first ruler of an Arab state to call on President Bashar al-Assad to "hand over power" in Syria, where some 40 civilians and members of the regime's military forces have been killed.
"If Bashar had the interests of his country at heart, he would have to resign, but he would also have to create the conditions necessary for a new phase of Syrian political life", the king of Jordan, a country bordering Syria, said in an interview with the BBC.
For his part, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoglu regretted that the efforts of Turkey to mediate with the Syrian regime since the beginning of the year had not been crowned with success.
"Those who cannot live in peace with their people and satisfy them in the Middle East will leave", he said, referring to neighboring Syria, which is facing an increasingly hard line from Turkey.
The United States welcomed the "strengthening of the consensus against Assad and the Syrian regime's disloyal behavior" following the decisions of the League of Arab States and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the European Union, the Arab League, countries like Turkey are taking a more and more harsh tone" toward the Syrian crackdown, noted Foreign Ministry spokesman Mark Toner.
The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights reported that 16 civilians and 19 pro-regime forces were killed in the southern Syrian city of Deraa during the same period.
According to the NGO, two other civilians were killed "in gunfire and concentrated heavy machine gun fire in the town of Jobar" in the Homs area.
But at a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Mouallem estimated that the country had "made its way out of the crisis".
He also reacted strongly to the decision of the League of Arab States to suspend Damascus as a member, which he described as a "dangerous step".
Syria "will not bow down", he added, assuring that "plots against Syria will not succeed".
Following its decision to suspend Syria's membership, the Arab League is currently considering a "civilian protection mechanism" and plans to send 500 human rights defenders, journalists and military observers to the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also favours the idea of sending UN observers to help protect civilians from the repression of a regime he says is behaving "paranoidly".
A new special League meeting is being called tomorrow in Rabat to take a position on the resolution plan agreed on December 2 that included, in particular, the withdrawal of the army from the cities beset by riots and the release of the imprisoned protesters.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov called the Arab League decision "wrong" yesterday, while China urged Syria to accept a plan to resolve the crisis, but completely avoided supporting any sanctions against Damascus.
