Soviet scientist helped the Iranian nuclear program
Soviet scientist Vyacheslav Danilenko helped Iran develop a detonator that could be used for a nuclear weapon, a U.S. non-governmental organization that specializes in nuclear risk reported Tuesday.
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is relying on a recent report from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and other documents leaked from the UN agency to identify the scientist.
Last week, the IAEA expressed its'serious concern' at the'possible military dimension' of Iran's nuclear programme.
According to the Institute of ISIS, which draws extensively from documents of the IAEA, V. Danilenko (born 1934) was supposed to have worked for three decades since the 1960s at the Soviet military research center in Chelyabinsk (Urals), where he was supposed to have been engaged in the production of synthetic diamonds by the method of explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he was supposed to leave the center to set up a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
He was responsible for the deaths of hundreds of people in the Ukrainian capital in the early 1990s.
He was subsequently involved in the Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002 before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA recalls 'clear indications that the development of the detonation system by Iran' was 'based on the work of a foreign specialist who was not only well-versed in the method but who, as one Member State has informed the Agency, had worked for a substantial part of his career on this technology within the framework of the military nuclear programme of his country of origin'.
Anti-Muslim crimes and misdemeanors increased by 50%
According to FBI statistics released Monday, the number of crimes and crimes against Muslims increased by nearly 50% from 2009 to 2010, while other racial and religious violence decreased slightly or barely increased during the same period.
According to these figures, the total number of violent crimes committed against Muslims rose from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, i.e. a 49% increase versus a 13% increase in violence against Catholics, a 4% decrease in anti-Jewish offences, and a 14% increase in anti-religious crimes and offences.
The total number of "hate crimes" rose very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3% were motivated by racial differences and 20% by religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is troubling to see these criminal acts and offences on the rise again", Human Rights First stressed, "the rise of anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant", the organisation added in its communiqué.
"Human Rights First has long emphasized that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be considered a serious violation of human rights", adds Paul Legendre, a senior official at the organization.
"The US government can and must do more to deal with these abuses", he adds, and estimates that this could be done by improving police reporting of "hate crimes".
"Hate crime" in American federal law is a legacy of the civil rights era.
This law was enacted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence based on race, color, religion, origin, and now sexual orientation.
