Austria
the inscription of the golden rule of balanced budgets in the Constitution
Austria's ruling Grand Coalition government of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats decided on Tuesday to write the "golden rule" of budgetary policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's rating by the AAA rating agencies.
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of the ministerial meeting, in a situation where Austria's public debt, at 74.6%, is well above the 60% maximum criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by just one single grade from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year", argued the chancellor and foreign minister, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus follows up on the request of the Eurozone Summit in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State and Government strongly requested that the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of a balance of public accounts be enshrined in the Constitution or an equivalent law by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the 'German model', Germany being the first European country to adopt such a 'rule'.
The public structural deficit will have to decrease by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year until 2017 and, from 2017, the federal state's public structural deficit will not be allowed to exceed 0,35% of GDP each year, while the Länder, as well as the municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The objective is to bring the public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
