Emergency threatens new intervention in foreign exchange markets
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese institutions would have to hit the foreign exchange markets again if he were to continue to tighten.
"We will intervene as we did last time if we find too much instability" in the exchange rate of the yen, explained Y. Noda to the Senate.
On Tuesday, it returned to the historical highs that forced Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo traded yen for dollars to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just broken a record against the dollar since 1945.
