Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was worth about 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This surge in the Japanese currency is damaging to island exports by raising the price of Made in Japan products and reducing the value of the profits that Japanese companies receive from abroad when they convert them into domestic currency.
"Japan is recovering" from the devastation caused by the March earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region in the northeast of the country, stressed Noda, who fears that the rise in the yen may not kill the fragile recovery in its infancy.
The world's third largest economy recovered in the third quarter (1.5% compared to the previous quarter) for the first time in a year, thanks to a survey of the growth of exports and household consumption burdened by the disaster.
But the prime minister felt that the high value of the yen did not reflect "the national economy of Japan".
Japanese Finance Minister Jun Azumi called on the Bank of Japan (BOJ), which began a two-day meeting of its political and monetary council on Tuesday, to take all measures to weaken the yen.
But the BoJ's deputy governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, noted that the BoJ had previously taken "patching measures" indicating that no further monetary weakness could be expected on Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the securities issuing institute increased its purchases of treasury notes by ¥5,000 billion (€47 billion) and raised the ceiling on the amount it devotes to purchases of various securities to flood it with liquidity to ¥55,000 billion (€519 billion).
