Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma
If there is a subject that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is natural that the election meeting should be an opportunity to reflect on such investments and the place that nuclear energy occupies.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are now 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic trends will cause electricity demands to double between now and 2050 unless we want to deprive a significant portion of the world's population of vital life components.
At the same time, we will have to face the shortage of fossil fuels to continue generating electricity, and we cannot forget the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that is currently missing from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident has no effect on any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
But this is not the case with Belgium, which is subordinating its decision to the need to find another source capable of replacing itself, or with Switzerland, which considers it right to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name just a few, are continuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to expand its park by one unit by rebuilding a power plant that had been suspended after the Three Mile Island power plant accident.
If the German model based on renewable energy is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts this.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in the price of electricity, the increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, the sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal-fired power plants.
All of these adverse effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves our consideration.
The European champion in wind power, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to the irregularity of the wind, which causes CO2 emissions and the prices of Danish electricity to be 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the contrary, thanks to the unchanged nature of our energy policy, our neighbors will pay 40% more in electricity bills than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the survival of industry on national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would cause a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful declarations about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, as well as not opposing this energy in principle, as opinion polls show.
It should be remembered that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to create a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 secondary jobs.
The highly export-oriented sector attracts a large number of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises to international markets, creating jobs which cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decided to abandon the nuclear power plant, it would sacrifice a significant number of these SMEs and lose the 6 billion euros per year the country earns from exporting nuclear equipment and services.
What power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to last 60 years while the manufacturer is scheduled to decay?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magic source for energy production, let alone any diabolical one.
The development of low-carbon installations, nuclear installations and installations using renewable energy sources by the French industrial group AREVA is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France we have the National Nuclear Safety Authority, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power stations as well as the construction of a new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is respected, have a notion of safety in their blood.
In the last 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island took place under normal traffic conditions and left no human casualties and no environmental consequences.
The Chernobyl tragedy was caused by the design of the reactor and by inexcusable human error.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident as it did from the previous two.
The EPR reactor is a design that can withstand such phenomena, the result of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers.
While all the interested parties who wish to build a nuclear power plant consider it, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to AREVA's and EDF's competitors and a way to give them a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solution for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogma and machinery control the debate so crucial to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the overcrowding of the police, the courts and the administration subject to the politics of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of "the land of human rights" that France boasts.
Recently, the administrative harassment of foreign students became a matter of concern when the Minister of the Interior (see Libération, 23 May) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it has rarely been analyzed from the standpoint of economics.
I have to say that there is a fairly broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
On the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone in 1976 when he said that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where there are 2 million migrant workers" and on the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of Polish plumbers on French soil was shared on both the right and the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity we are willing to extend to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande limits himself to platitudes when he says that joint development will solve our 'migration problem'.
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem is valid maybe in elections, but it's very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in their recently published work summarising the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, p. 352), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration is holding back growth and hurting employment.
The fears of the impact of migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially those with lower qualifications, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that in reality immigrants are much more than substitutes for French workers, performing jobs in sectors where there is a shortage of workers.
There are few skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not enough to fill the job market.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementary differences between French and migrants cause the arrival of immigrants to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of French employees.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements will cause a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And it ignores the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, on average, of 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution to the public budget (income minus expenditure) of €150,000 over his or her lifetime.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed the wish to go for the missing growth rate "with a precious tooth".
The teeth mentioned to repel immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, what remains to be done is to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious and very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, because although it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it has experienced the tragedies of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag in the 20th century, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some people may believe that for democracy to triumph over its enemies, it will be enough to make the choice and make it as honest as possible.
But it's been known since Napoleon that it was about ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become, as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once put it, a 'machine of oppression'.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, and from the very beginning, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The admission of the error of the Greek referendum of the yes-no type will have the double effect of revealing the need for a great return to political power, but also revealing the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be thought through to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We can achieve nothing by calling for a series of national referendums, organized by necessity and disorganized.
To be exposed to Europe's absolutist monarch or to plunge with bound feet into the hollow of nationalist depths: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we don't want the knives of the guillotine, but a joint, full-fledged, peaceful and uninterrupted exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we wouldn't even know where to stop counting - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe bowing to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffers from its own incompetence and its own lack of solidarity.
It is all of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are worried about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the European project to democratic sovereignty.
Only together can Europeans reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the domination of the markets and invest for the future.
The solution to the crisis will require decisions at European level, which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise we will be in for disaster.
After long struggles against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now insisting on a European economic government.
Be there.
But to think that without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must embark on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To create a republic in France, you had to "be" a republican.
A revolution of interest was not enough.
This lesson remains.
We must build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This can only be done by building a Europe that is more politically democratic and a true European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans to build Europe.
Contactless chip cards are spreading
In an atmosphere of optimism, the world's fair for the chip card will open Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris.
According to the Eurosmart cabinet, 2011 should end with an increase of 11% in worldwide sales of micro-processor cards (bank cards, SIM-card phones) to more than 6 billion units.
The most prominent segment is contactless technology, which allows payment in mass transport or purchases to be processed simply by bringing the card closer to the reader.
This year, 460 million cards with chips are expected to be sold worldwide, compared with 320 million sold the year before!
Their share is expected to increase further in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and to reach approximately 10% of the total chip card market (6,925 million cards).
After being dragged by APEC countries for a long time, Europe is gaining ground in contactless payments.
Approximately 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards have been issued.
But the big chain stores work for two.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
To incorporate a higher rate, banks must now provide it to their clients.
"Two major French companies have committed themselves to systematically distributing contactless bank cards to their customers in the future", says Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa France Europe.
Banks test mobile payments
But that's just the first step toward the payment device of the future: the mobile phone.
Only a small number of devices are equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology required for transaction processing.
"They were not late".
"But their true flourishing should come in the next year".
"We estimate that between 80 and 120 million of these will be sold worldwide in 2012", explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks are already preparing ahead.
Yesterday, Crédit Agricole announced the launch of a trial in the city of Caen, which will run from December to June next year.
Approximately 200 clients and associates will have their iPhones equipped with a contactless payment enabled case.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And also, yesterday, Société Générale announced that it was preparing to introduce a mobile-phone contactless payment option for its clients.
The terrorist front stretches from the Sahara to Nigeria.
Paris is concerned about the links between Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Long-standing suspicions that there are links between the Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQMI) terrorist group and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even admitted that Algeria was now "certain" of this.
"The way the two organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that there is a lot of cooperation between them", he explained without elaborating.
Paris seems to have similar analyses.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two French nationals in Niger in January 2010 could help to shed light on the connecting bridges.
After the abduction of AQMI members from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day, along with several of their captors, in an operation carried out by French special forces.
In the rubble of the attack, French and Nigerian investigators found several phones with chips belonging to terrorists.
The axis of terrorism
Analysis of the calls made leads to several people in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers in particular are of interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who had spent time in Maiduguri, the northern city of Boko Haram, and the other to a man said to be close to AQIM and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must wait for more convincing evidence before we can talk about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more and more active", says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian investigator.
In recent months, this 'support' has become increasingly apparent in the development and manifestations of Boko Haram or its operational practices, which now include human casualties or increasingly complex explosive devices of the same design as those used by AQMI.
The international community, led by Washington, has since put pressure on Nigeria to address the problems posed by Boko Haram.
In fact, the Nigerian authorities have long considered the group to be a community of enlightened mystics of little interest.
A Quick Success
Boko Haram was founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf. Boko Haram, which means "Western education is sin" in the Hausa language, endorses the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, such a connection is a quick success.
The sect is politicized and demands strict adherence to Islamic Sharia law, while its followers wage a war against the central government.
These people are focusing on churches, bars, and government offices first.
In 2009, Boko Haram followers became extraordinarily active and increased their attacks against police stations.
