Nord Stream, the new port of entry for Russian gas into Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which links Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has started operating.
They have to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the occasion properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte together turned the controls around on the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
This new pipeline will start to deliver an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe each year via the first 1 224 km pipeline linking the St Petersburg region with the federal state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, due to be completed by the end of 2012, will deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And it's already being mentioned that there's a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction project is a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being piped across the country by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As these two countries lose some power, it becomes more difficult for them to pressure Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
Warsaw expressed this most forcefully when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the 1939 occupation of Poland.
It means to say that this is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it comes at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from the East and the West.
Russia barely managed to get its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-hungry Western states, whose deposits are coming to an end, through five years ago.
'This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,' said François Fillon at the opening ceremony, demonstrating the political and economic importance of the big gas contracts.
This explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a major engineering feat.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from the anchors of naval vessels.
It rests on the sea floor at an average depth of 200 m.
The construction was to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"For safety reasons, almost 100 of them had to be removed or destroyed", says Jens Müller, a Nord Stream spokesman.
Measures to protect the flora and fauna also had to be stepped up.
The pipeline itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffel Towers, uninterrupted by any valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it, as the Swedes were only slightly keen to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up on their shores.
"In the event of a malfunction, we can stop the gas leak in less than 1 minute", says Jens Müller.
If the gas is not sealed, the gas in the pipeline will leak into the air.
But this is considered unlikely by the builders, because the welding was designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The outside of the pipeline is controlled by a submarine robot pulled by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This 1 metre diameter cigar shaped device is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pressed with gas.
The target after three full days of travel at 3 m/s will provide accurate information on any deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply provided by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains the leader with a 51% stake.
It was joined by E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and Gasunie in the Netherlands and GDF Suez in France (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely favourable.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transport capacity to this company for five years under a renewable contract.
'Gazprom will have a profit on the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,' explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez group, the investment costs thus amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be recovered, as Gazprom alone bears the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves are 15 feet high and form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature, and other characteristics of incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
As of last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - the brand log
Founded 50 years ago, the Italian firm Moleskine wants to bring back the joy of writing.
It brings the smell of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine is easily recognized by its black rectangular plates and its white-colored leaves that seem aged by time.
After all, the Moleskine Notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a new design, but a distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, a consultant working for the company at the time, misses the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique of 'moleskin' (imitation of leather), which is used for example to finish the surface of the benches.
This type of notebook was highly prized by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has brought back to life an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Sales rose by 26% between 2006 and 2010 to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is a remote, hidden production from the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to construct an artificial image of the buyer, since the notebook will be as interesting to businessmen as to students or professionals.
The image of the Moleskine notebook is that its owners are people of cosmopolitan, cultured and open spirit.
A small Italian company that started with 12 employees has grown to almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks to bookstores and through the FNAC chain of stores to small boutiques in the city centers, where he has been able to assert his identity.
"We followed the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, despite the stormy development of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature has accompanied the development of the Moleskine notebook: the brand recently opened the exhibition 'Zacházka', where architects or artists display their notebook.
In August, she also introduced new notebook plates resembling leopards at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine is capitalizing on its success and this cultural aura and diversifying its products: bags, pens, pencils, laptop cases... The brand is expanding to a whole range of media.
A success that aroused envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment funds SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed handicapped workers?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today marks the 15th anniversary of the handicapped employment week.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is still twice the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the whole population.
Is that depressing?
"No", stresses Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, which organises Employment Week for the Disabled.
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher".
"However, much remains to be done".
It should be noted that for unemployed disabled people, many obstacles remain before they enter the workforce.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (on average 17%).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a diploma and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10 000 are handicapped.
And finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make re-entry particularly difficult and are the 'core of the problem', according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was set up in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association found that managers surveyed had 'a poor level of knowledge about disabled people' with 'an exaggerated view of people in wheelchairs and of mental or mental disabilities'.
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set by the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, give a rate of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, the director general of Agefiph, an organisation charged with collecting fees from companies that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of 'penalised' enterprises, as well as by the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million) between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 law that increased contributions has put a lot of pressure on businesses", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates a real awareness, especially in large enterprises".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
